INTRODUCTION

In this project we focused on predicting customer churn in the telecommuncations industry using the Telco Customer Churn dataset from Kaggle. Customer churn is a significant challenge for telecom providers because keeping existing customers is more cost-effective than getting new ones. The aim is to build machine learning models that can detect-prone customers and support retention strategies.

DATASET

This dataset contains 7043 customer records with demographic, contract, billing, and service usage features. The target is variable Churn. The main challenge in this dataset is class imbalance: around 27% of customers churned while 73%stayed, which means this imbalance was handled using SMOTE during preprocessing.

EDA

We followed these paths in the eda phase: Demographics: Senior citizens and single-person households churn more often.

Services: Customers with fiber optic internet and those without online security or tech support have the highest churn.

Contracts: Month-to-month contracts show extremely high churn (~43%), while long-term contracts strongly reduce churn.

Billing: Customers paying by electronic check churn the most (~45%).

These findings align with previous research and provide useful business insights.

#EDA
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

#the pallets we will use
PALETTES = {
    "neutral": ["#4C78A8"],
    "rainbow": ["#4C78A8","#F58518","#E45756","#72B7B2","#54A24B","#EECA3B","#B279A2"],
    "cool":    ["#3B8CCC","#86B6E2","#C7DBF0"],
    "warm":    ["#F1696C","#F59D7A","#F7C59F"],
    "qual":    ["#4C78A8","#F58518","#E45756","#72B7B2","#54A24B","#EECA3B","#B279A2","#FF9DA6"],
    "internet": ["#8F8F8F","#4C78A8","#E45756"],          # No / DSL / Fiber optic
    "contract": ["#E45756","#F58518","#54A24B"],          # Month-to-month / One / Two year
    "payment":  ["#E45756","#4C78A8","#54A24B","#B279A2","#F58518","#72B7B2"]
}

def _apply_colors(ax, n, palette):
    pal = PALETTES.get(palette, PALETTES["neutral"])
    colors = (pal * (n // len(pal) + 1))[:n]
    for bar, c in zip(ax.patches, colors):
        bar.set_color(c)

def plot_rate_by_category(data, category, title, order=None, rot=0, figsize=(6.6,4.6), palette="neutral"):
    if category not in data.columns:
        print(f"[Skip] {category}"); return
    tmp = (data.dropna(subset=[category])
              .groupby(category, dropna=False)["Churn01"].mean().reset_index())
    if tmp.empty:
        print(f"[Skip] {category} empty"); return
    if order is not None:
        tmp[category] = pd.Categorical(tmp[category], categories=order, ordered=True)
        tmp = tmp.sort_values(category)
    else:
        tmp = tmp.sort_values("Churn01", ascending=False)

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=figsize)
    ax.bar(tmp[category].astype(str), (tmp["Churn01"]*100))
    _apply_colors(ax, len(tmp), palette)
    for i, v in enumerate(tmp["Churn01"]*100):
        ax.text(i, v+0.6, f"{v:.1f}%", ha="center", va="bottom", fontsize=9)
    ax.set_title(title); ax.set_ylabel("Churn rate (%)"); ax.set_xlabel(category)
    plt.xticks(rotation=rot)
    plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()

def plot_rate_vs_numeric(data, num_col, bins=10, title=None, figsize=(6.8,4.6), line_color="#4C78A8"):
    if num_col not in data.columns:
        print(f"[Skip] {num_col}"); return
    d = data[[num_col,"Churn01"]].dropna().copy()
    if d.empty:
        print(f"[Skip] {num_col} empty"); return
    try:
        q = np.quantile(d[num_col], np.linspace(0,1,bins+1))
        q = np.unique(q)
        if len(q) < 3:
            d["bin"] = pd.qcut(d[num_col], q=bins, duplicates="drop")
        else:
            d["bin"] = pd.cut(d[num_col], bins=q, include_lowest=True)
    except Exception:
        d["bin"] = pd.qcut(d[num_col], q=bins, duplicates="drop")
    grp = d.groupby("bin")["Churn01"].mean().reset_index()
    x, y = grp["bin"].astype(str), grp["Churn01"]*100

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=figsize)
    ax.plot(range(len(x)), y, marker="o", linewidth=2, color=line_color)
    ax.set_xticks(range(len(x))); ax.set_xticklabels(x, rotation=60, ha="right")
    ax.set_ylabel("Churn rate (%)"); ax.set_title(title or f"Churn rate vs {num_col}")
    plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()

def corr_heatmap(df_, cols, title="Correlation heatmap", cmap="coolwarm", annot=True, figsize=(6.4,5.2)):
    use = [c for c in cols if c in df_.columns]
    if len(use) < 3:
        print(f"[Skip] not enough cols: {use}"); return
    d = df_[use].dropna().copy()
    if d.empty:
        print("[Skip] no rows after NaN drop"); return
    c = d.corr(numeric_only=True)

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=figsize)
    im = ax.imshow(c, interpolation="nearest", cmap=cmap)
    ax.set_title(title)
    fig.colorbar(im, fraction=0.046, pad=0.04)
    ax.set_xticks(range(len(c.columns))); ax.set_xticklabels(c.columns, rotation=45, ha="right")
    ax.set_yticks(range(len(c.index))); ax.set_yticklabels(c.index)
    if annot:
        for i in range(c.shape[0]):
            for j in range(c.shape[1]):
                ax.text(j, i, f"{c.values[i,j]:.2f}", ha="center", va="center", fontsize=8, color="black")
    plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()

    print("VIF iÃ§in statsmodels gerekli. Gerekirse: !pip install -q statsmodels")

num_cols3 = dfm.select_dtypes(include=["int64","float64"]).columns.tolist()
X_num = dfm[num_cols3].copy().fillna(dfm[num_cols3].median())
X_num = sm.add_constant(X_num)

vif_rows = []
for i, col in enumerate(X_num.columns):
    if col == "const":
        continue
    vif = variance_inflation_factor(X_num.values, i)
    vif_rows.append({"feature": col, "VIF": round(vif, 3)})
display(pd.DataFrame(vif_rows).sort_values("VIF", ascending=False))

PREPROCESSING

Missing values were imputed (median for numeric, most frequent for categorical).

Categorical variables were transformed using One-Hot Encoding (handle_unknown="ignore").

Numerical variables were scaled with StandardScaler for logistic regression and neural networks.

SMOTE was applied to balance the minority class (churn = 1).

Two preprocessing pipelines were created:

One for models that need to scale, such as Logistic Regression, Artificial Neural Networks.

One for tree-based models such as Random Forest, XGBoost, where scaling is not required.

#Preprocessing
try:
    OHE = OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown="ignore", sparse_output=False)  #>=1.2
except TypeError:
    OHE = OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown="ignore", sparse=False)         #<1.2

pre_lr = ColumnTransformer([
    ("num", Pipeline([("imp", SimpleImputer(strategy="median")),
                      ("sc",  StandardScaler(with_mean=True))]), num_cols),
    ("cat", Pipeline([("imp", SimpleImputer(strategy="most_frequent")),
                      ("oh",  OHE)]), cat_cols),
])

pre_tree = ColumnTransformer([
    ("num", SimpleImputer(strategy="median"), num_cols),
    ("cat", Pipeline([("imp", SimpleImputer(strategy="most_frequent")),
                      ("oh",  OHE)]), cat_cols),
])

Numeric features are imputed (median) and scaled; categorical features are imputed (most frequent) and one-hot encoded with handle_unknown='ignore'. For tree models we skip scaling, but keep imputation and one-hot encoding.

InÂ [72]:
#Train models such as Dummy, LR, RF, XGB printing metrics (ACC, PREC, REC, F1, ROC-AUC, PR-AP)

def print_metrics(y_true, proba, label, thr=0.5):
    pred = (proba >= thr).astype(int)
    ACC  = accuracy_score(y_true, pred)
    PREC = precision_score(y_true, pred, zero_division=0)
    REC  = recall_score(y_true, pred, zero_division=0)
    F1   = f1_score(y_true, pred, zero_division=0)
    AUC  = roc_auc_score(y_true, proba)
    AP   = average_precision_score(y_true, proba)
    print(f"{label} | ACC={ACC:.3f} PREC={PREC:.3f} REC={REC:.3f} F1={F1:.3f}  ROC-AUC={AUC:.3f} PR-AP={AP:.3f}")
    return {"label":label,"acc":ACC,"prec":PREC,"rec":REC,"f1":F1,"auc":AUC,"ap":AP}

# Class imbalance (XGB)
pos = y_train.sum(); neg = len(y_train) - pos
spw = (neg / pos) if pos else 1.0

# Dummy
pipe_dummy = Pipeline([("pre", pre_tree), ("clf", DummyClassifier(strategy="stratified", random_state=RANDOM_STATE))])
pipe_dummy.fit(X_train, y_train); proba_dummy = pipe_dummy.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
res_dummy = print_metrics(y_test, proba_dummy, "Dummy")

# Logistic Regression
pipe_lr = Pipeline([("pre", pre_lr),
                    ("clf", LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, class_weight="balanced",
                                               solver="liblinear", random_state=RANDOM_STATE))])
pipe_lr.fit(X_train, y_train); proba_lr = pipe_lr.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
res_lr = print_metrics(y_test, proba_lr, "LR")

# Random Forest
pipe_rf = Pipeline([("pre", pre_tree),
                    ("clf", RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=400, class_weight="balanced_subsample",
                                                  n_jobs=-1, random_state=RANDOM_STATE))])
pipe_rf.fit(X_train, y_train); proba_rf = pipe_rf.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
res_rf = print_metrics(y_test, proba_rf, "RF")

# XGBoost
pipe_xgb = Pipeline([("pre", pre_tree),
                     ("clf", XGBClassifier(n_estimators=500, learning_rate=0.05, max_depth=4,
                                           subsample=0.8, colsample_bytree=0.8,
                                           objective="binary:logistic", eval_metric="logloss",
                                           n_jobs=-1, random_state=RANDOM_STATE,
                                           scale_pos_weight=spw))])
pipe_xgb.fit(X_train, y_train); proba_xgb = pipe_xgb.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
res_xgb = print_metrics(y_test, proba_xgb, "XGB")

#Precision/Recall vs Threshold (Best model)
if proba_best is not None:
    ths = np.linspace(0.05, 0.95, 19)
    precs, recs = [], []
    for t in ths:
        pred = (proba_best >= t).astype(int)
        precs.append(precision_score(y_test, pred, zero_division=0))
        recs.append(recall_score(y_test, pred))
    plt.figure(figsize=(6.4,4.4))
    plt.plot(ths, precs, marker="o", label="Precision", lw=2)
    plt.plot(ths, recs,  marker="o", label="Recall",    lw=2)
    plt.xlabel("Threshold"); plt.ylabel("Score"); plt.title(f"Precision/Recall vs Threshold â {best_label}")
    plt.legend(frameon=False); plt.grid(alpha=.25); plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()

As the threshold increases, precision goes up while recall goes down. Choose the threshold based on business costâe.g., around the point where precision and recall balance for your use case.

Results | Model Comparison

Logistic Regression (balanced): Highest ROC-AUC (0.841) â best interpretability.

XGBoost: Highest average precision (0.649) + strong recall â best predictive performance.

Random Forest: Solid baseline (AUC 0.823), but below LR and XGB.

Neural Network: Competitive with XGBoost on recall, but less precision and more complexity.

XGBoost balances precision and recall better than other models, making it the most reliable for detecting churners in practice. Its ability to handle imbalanced data and capture feature interactions explains why it performs best. Although XGBoost predicts slightly better, Logistic Regression remains the most interpretable model. Its coefficients and SHAP/LIME explanations make it suitable when business transparency and regulatory requirements are critical.

Conclusion

This study demonstrates that both traditional and advanced machine learning models can be applied successfully for churn prediction in the telecom industry. XGBoost provided the best predictive performance overall, achieving the highest average precision and recall balance, while Logistic Regression offered the best interpretability with the highest ROC-AUC. Random Forest also showed stable results, and Neural Networks performed competitively but with added complexity.

By combining predictive power (XGBoost) and interpretability (Logistic Regression), telecom providers can achieve both accurate and actionable churn prediction. These findings align with previous studies, confirming that ensemble models like XGBoost are optimal for performance, whereas Logistic Regression remains essential for explainability
